{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9767df68ffcbe964", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tContext-Aware ASR for Mandarin Technical Lectures\n2\tHo-Lam Chung1,2 , Yiming Chen2 , Hung-yi Lee1\n3\t1\n4\t\n5\tNational Taiwan University, Taiwan\n6\t\n7\t2\n8\t\n9\tASUS\n10\t\n11\tholam.chung@protonmail.com, yiming.chen@u.nus.edu, tlkagkb93901106@gmail.com\n12\t\n13\tarXiv:2607.05058v1 [cs.SD] 6 Jul 2026\n14\t\n15\tAbstract\n16\tTechnical lectures mix Mandarin speech with English technical terms. These terms carry the core meaning of the lecture,\n17\tyet they occupy few characters. Character error rate (CER)\n18\ttherefore hides their recognition failures. We study whether\n19\tlecture context helps recognize these terms. We build a termrich Mandarin AI/ML lecture benchmark, and we define termcentric metrics that measure technical-term recognition directly.\n20\tWe then propose a two-pass, reference-free decoding method.\n21\tThe first pass runs segment-only ASR. We extract the most frequent technical terms from the first-pass hypotheses, and we\n22\tprompt the recognizer with this self-built glossary in the second pass. Across five ASR backbones, the first-pass glossary\n23\traises term recall for every model and holds or lowers CER on\n24\tall five. On Breeze-ASR-25 it lifts term recall from 52.50% to\n25\t60.13% while lowering CER, and a hybrid that adds a small\n26\texternal term list reaches 62.05% recall and 82.73% term precision. Lecture context, recovered from the model’s own output,\n27\tis a practical signal for technical-term recognition. Term-centric\n28\tevaluation exposes errors that CER misses.\n29\tIndex Terms: speech recognition, code-switching, contextual\n30\tbiasing, technical terms, Mandarin\n31\t\n32\t1. Introduction\n33\tLecture ASR powers subtitles, search, and note-taking for students. In AI/ML lectures, bilingual technical terms anchor the\n34\tcontent. Terms such as RAG, SWE-bench, AI Agent, token, and\n35\tembedding name the concepts the speaker explains. A student\n36\twho reads “RIG” instead of “RAG” loses the point of the segment.\n37\tThese terms occupy a small fraction of the characters. A\n38\ttranscript can reach low CER while still misrecognizing the key\n39\tterm. The Mandarin around the term is fluent, so CER stays low.\n40\tThe usable content, however, is wrong. CER does not capture\n41\tthis failure.\n42\tLecture terms are bursty. Once the speaker introduces AI\n43\tAgent, the term recurs across many later segments. The lecture\n44\ttitle, the previous transcript, and the repeated terms all point\n45\tto the same vocabulary. Segment-only decoding discards this\n46\tsignal. It recognizes each segment in isolation, so it cannot use\n47\tthe strong context that the lecture provides.\n48\tWe address this gap by building a term-rich benchmark,\n49\tmeasuring term recognition directly, and supplying a self-built\n50\tglossary as decoding context.\n51\tOur contributions are as follows.\n52\t• We release a term-rich Mandarin AI/ML lecture ASR\n53\tbenchmark. It contains 8,888 technical-term occurrences\n54\tover a 5.01-hour code-switched test set.\n55\t• We define term-centric evaluation. It reports term recall,\n56\tterm precision, term F1, and term error rate, so it separates technical-term accuracy from overall CER.\n57\t\n58\t• We propose a two-pass, reference-free glossary prompt.\n59\tIt extracts a lecture glossary from first-pass hypotheses,\n60\tand it improves term recall across five ASR backbones\n61\twhile holding or lowering CER on all of them. A hybrid\n62\tthat adds a small external glossary reaches 62.05% term\n63\trecall on Breeze-ASR-25, closing part of the remaining\n64\theadroom.\n65\t\n66\t2. Related Work\n67\tCode-switching Mandarin-English ASR. Mandarin-English\n68\tcode-switching is a long-standing challenge for ASR. Public\n69\tcorpora such as SEAME [1], the ASRU 2019 challenge set [2],\n70\tand ASCEND [3] established Mandarin-English benchmarks,\n71\tbut they target conversational rather than lecture speech. Recent work fine-tunes large models on Mandarin with English\n72\tterms [4], and distills language-specific knowledge for codeswitching [5]. These methods improve the acoustic model. We\n73\tinstead keep the model frozen, and we add context at decoding\n74\ttime.\n75\tContextual biasing. Contextual ASR injects external\n76\tknowledge into recognition. Deep context learns to bias toward a phrase list [6]. Trie-based deep biasing and shallow fusion bias streaming recognizers toward a catalog [7]. Audiolanguage models couple speech encoders with LLMs [8, 9],\n77\tand LLM-based recognizers consume free-form context [10].\n78\tQwen3-ASR treats context tokens as background knowledge\n79\tfor biasing [11]. These methods assume a context source is\n80\tavailable. We build the context from the model’s own first-pass\n81\toutput, so the method needs no external list.\n82\tPrompting and retrieval. Whisper accepts an initial\n83\tprompt that conditions decoding [12]. Two-pass ASR refines\n84\tfirst-pass output, either by rescoring streamed hypotheses with\n85\ta second decoder [13, 14] or by correcting the first-pass N-best\n86\tlist with an LLM [15]. Retrieval-augmented generation supplies retrieved evidence to a generator [16]. Our two-pass glossary is an in-domain analogue: the first pass retrieves over the\n87\tlecture itself, and the second pass conditions on the retrieved\n88\tterms. Unlike rescoring or correction, we feed the terms back\n89\tas context rather than editing the hypotheses, and we derive that\n90\tlist from the model’s own lecture-level output, so the method is\n91\treference-free.\n92\t\n93\t3. Benchmark\n94\tWe build the benchmark from a publicly available MandarinEnglish AI/ML lecture series1 . The lectures are spontaneous\n95\tspeech, with English technical terms code-switched into Mandarin. We segment the lectures and pair each segment with its\n96\treference transcript.\n97\tWe then build a term-rich test set. A rule-based recognizer\n98\textracts technical terms from the reference transcripts. It tar1 Dataset, code, and term metadata will be released upon publication.\n99\t\n100\t\fTable 1: Benchmark statistics. The term-rich test set isolates\n101\tsegments that contain at least one technical term.\n102\tItem\n103\t\n104\tValue\n105\t\n106\tFull set segments\n107\tFull set duration\n108\tTerm-rich segments\n109\tTerm-rich duration\n110\tTerm occurrences\n111\tUnique canonical terms\n112\tLectures\n113\t\n114\t29,043\n115\t16.92 h\n116\t7,443\n117\t5.01 h\n118\t8,888\n119\t1,030\n120\t15\n121\t\n122\ttoken\n123\tAI\n124\tattention\n125\tprompt\n126\tAI Agent\n127\tembedding\n128\tcontext\n129\tagent\n130\tOpenClaw\n131\tsequence\n132\tLlama\n133\tlayer\n134\t\n135\t230\n136\t204\n137\t176\n138\t135\n139\t132\n140\t116\n141\t108\n142\t\n143\t0\n144\t\n145\t372\n146\t338\n147\t312\n148\t292\n149\t\n150\t784\n151\t\n152\t200\n153\t400\n154\t600\n155\t800\n156\tOccurrences in term-rich test set\n157\t\n158\tFigure 1: Technical-term frequency in the term-rich test set, top\n159\t12 terms. The distribution is heavy-tailed. The lecture-specific\n160\ttool name OpenClaw (red) occurs 135 times, which shows that\n161\teven a name the model has never seen repeats heavily within\n162\tone lecture.\n163\t\n164\tgets four kinds of terms: acronyms such as AI and LLM; model\n165\tand tool names such as Llama, Whisper, and OpenClaw; codelike strings such as SWE-bench and log1.txt; and multi-word\n166\tterms such as AI Agent and Context Engineering. We canonicalize each term with NFKC normalization, lowercasing, and\n167\tlight stemming, so surface variants map to one key. A segment\n168\tenters the term-rich set when it contains at least one term.\n169\tTable 1 summarizes the benchmark. The full set has 29,043\n170\tsegments and 16.92 hours. The term-rich test set has 7,443 segments and 5.01 hours, with 8,888 term occurrences and 1,030\n171\tunique terms over 15 lectures. Terms are bursty. Fig. 1 shows\n172\tthe term frequencies. The term token occurs 784 times, AI\n173\tAgent 292 times, and the lecture-specific name OpenClaw 135\n174\ttimes. This burstiness is the signal that motivates lecture-level\n175\tcontext. The distribution is heavy-tailed: acronyms and short\n176\tmodel names lead the head, while multi-word terms and codelike strings fill the tail. A method must handle both the frequent\n177\tacronyms and the rare composite names.\n178\t\n179\t4. Term-Centric Evaluation\n180\tCER measures character accuracy over the whole segment. It\n181\tdoes not tell us whether the recognizer captured the technical\n182\tterms. We therefore add four term-centric metrics. We compute\n183\tthem over canonical term keys.\n184\tWe define term recall as the fraction of reference term oc-\n185\t\n186\tTable 2: Segment-only baselines. CER is computed on the full\n187\t16.92 h set; term metrics on the 5.01 h term-rich subset. All\n188\tvalues are percentages. Bold marks the best column value,\n189\tunderline the second best. Lower is better for CER and TermER; higher is better otherwise.\n190\tModel\n191\t\n192\tCER\n193\t\n194\tRecall\n195\t\n196\tPrec.\n197\t\n198\tF1\n199\t\n200\tTermER\n201\t\n202\tBreeze-ASR-25\n203\twhisper-l-v3-turbo\n204\tQwen3-ASR-1.7B\n205\tQwen3-ASR-0.6B\n206\tBreeze-ASR-26\n207\t\n208\t10.72\n209\t11.95\n210\t15.28\n211\t16.64\n212\t24.63\n213\t\n214\t52.50\n215\t53.90\n216\t49.03\n217\t44.28\n218\t27.31\n219\t\n220\t80.55\n221\t65.11\n222\t72.84\n223\t71.19\n224\t56.26\n225\t\n226\t63.57\n227\t58.98\n228\t58.61\n229\t54.60\n230\t36.77\n231\t\n232\t48.66\n233\t49.67\n234\t53.31\n235\t58.20\n236\t75.14\n237\t\n238\tcurrences whose canonical key appears in the hypothesis of the\n239\tsame segment. We define term precision as the fraction of predicted term keys that appear in the reference. We define term F1\n240\tas their harmonic mean. We define term error rate as the edit\n241\tdistance between the reference and hypothesis term sequences,\n242\tnormalized by the reference term count.\n243\tWe keep CER as the overall accuracy measure. We normalize all Mandarin text with OpenCC2 (s2twp) and apply NFKC\n244\tand lowercasing before scoring. A usable transcript needs both\n245\thigh recall and high precision, and CER captures neither. The\n246\ttwo metrics can move in opposite directions: a recognizer that\n247\tcopies a long context into its output raises recall while collapsing precision, as Table 3 shows. We therefore report recall and\n248\tprecision together, and treat term recall as the headline metric\n249\tbecause it counts how many technical terms the recognizer recovered.\n250\tTable 2 reports five recognizers under segment-only decoding. Breeze-ASR-25 has the best CER and the best term error\n251\trate. Yet it recovers only 52.50% of the terms. Whisper-largev3-turbo has slightly higher term recall but much lower term\n252\tprecision. Every model leaves a large share of technical terms\n253\tunrecognized. A low CER does not imply usable technical transcripts.\n254\t\n255\t5. Method\n256\tWe propose a two-pass, reference-free decoding method. We\n257\tcall it ASR - GLOSSARY. The idea is simple. A lecture repeats\n258\tits terms, so the model’s own first-pass output already contains\n259\tthose terms. We collect them, and we feed them back as context.\n260\tAlgorithm 1 states the procedure. The first pass runs\n261\tsegment-only ASR over the lecture. We extract canonical terms\n262\tfrom every first-pass hypothesis, and we rank them by frequency across the lecture. We keep the top k surface forms\n263\tas the first-pass glossary. The second pass re-decodes each segment with this glossary as context.\n264\tWe set k = 30. A short glossary keeps the prompt compact,\n265\tso it avoids over-conditioning. Frequency ranking captures the\n266\tbursty repeats, so the glossary holds the terms that matter for\n267\tthis lecture. A sweep over k (Sec. 6.1) confirms that k = 30\n268\tgives the lowest CER, and a selection ablation confirms that\n269\tlecture-level frequency, not the mere presence of a term, is the\n270\tsignal that matters. We use the surface form, so the prompt\n271\treads like natural text.\n272\tConditioning interface. The two model families consume\n273\tthe glossary differently. For Whisper-family models, including Breeze, we pass the glossary as an initial prompt through\n274\tprompt tokens. We apply it to the first decoding window, we\n275\t2 https://github.com/BYVoid/OpenCC\n276\t\n277\t\fTable 3: Contextual decoding across five ASR backbones on the 5.01 h term-rich set. CER is rescored on this subset, so baselines match\n278\tthe contextual rows. ∆R is the term-recall gain over the baseline. ⋆ marks the proposed reference-free prompt. Bold marks the best\n279\tvalue per column within each model. Values are percentages; lower is better for CER and TermER.\n280\t\n281\tModel\n282\t\n283\tContext\n284\t\n285\tCER\n286\t\n287\tRecall\n288\t\n289\t∆R\n290\t\n291\tPrec.\n292\t\n293\tF1\n294\t\n295\tTermER\n296\t\n297\tBreeze-ASR-25\n298\t\n299\tbaseline (segment-only)\n300\t+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n301\t+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n302\t\n303\t11.37\n304\t9.79\n305\t9.19\n306\t\n307\t52.50\n308\t60.13\n309\t59.51\n310\t\n311\t–\n312\t+7.63\n313\t+7.01\n314\t\n315\t80.55\n316\t81.20\n317\t82.19\n318\t\n319\t63.57\n320\t69.09\n321\t69.03\n322\t\n323\t48.66\n324\t41.38\n325\t41.74\n326\t\n327\twhisper-l-v3-turbo\n328\t\n329\tbaseline (segment-only)\n330\t+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n331\t+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n332\t\n333\t13.80\n334\t12.82\n335\t15.89\n336\t\n337\t53.90\n338\t60.86\n339\t59.74\n340\t\n341\t–\n342\t+6.95\n343\t+5.84\n344\t\n345\t65.11\n346\t63.79\n347\t65.03\n348\t\n349\t58.98\n350\t62.29\n351\t62.28\n352\t\n353\t49.67\n354\t45.93\n355\t48.77\n356\t\n357\tQwen3-ASR-1.7B\n358\t\n359\tbaseline (segment-only)\n360\t+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n361\t+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n362\t\n363\t16.13\n364\t14.02\n365\t13.93\n366\t\n367\t49.03\n368\t56.56\n369\t56.60\n370\t\n371\t–\n372\t+7.53\n373\t+7.57\n374\t\n375\t72.84\n376\t74.43\n377\t76.11\n378\t\n379\t58.61\n380\t64.27\n381\t64.92\n382\t\n383\t53.31\n384\t47.10\n385\t46.26\n386\t\n387\tQwen3-ASR-0.6B\n388\t\n389\tbaseline (segment-only)\n390\t+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n391\t+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n392\t\n393\t18.91\n394\t18.86\n395\t25.39\n396\t\n397\t44.28\n398\t53.74\n399\t54.43\n400\t\n401\t–\n402\t+9.45\n403\t+10.15\n404\t\n405\t71.19\n406\t65.92\n407\t59.79\n408\t\n409\t54.60\n410\t59.21\n411\t56.99\n412\t\n413\t58.20\n414\t54.64\n415\t64.99\n416\t\n417\tBreeze-ASR-26\n418\t\n419\tbaseline (segment-only)\n420\t+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n421\t+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n422\t\n423\t38.28\n424\t26.05\n425\t21.67\n426\t\n427\t27.31\n428\t44.89\n429\t49.73\n430\t\n431\t–\n432\t+17.59\n433\t+22.42\n434\t\n435\t56.26\n436\t57.15\n437\t63.32\n438\t\n439\t36.77\n440\t50.28\n441\t55.71\n442\t\n443\t75.14\n444\t62.27\n445\t54.53\n446\t\n447\tAlgorithm 1 Two-pass glossary-prompted decoding\n448\tRequire: lecture segments S = {s1 , . . . , sn }, recognizer M ,\n449\tglossary size k\n450\t1: Pass 1: hi ← M (si ) for all si\n451\t▷ segment-only\n452\t2: C ← C OUNTER()\n453\t3: for each hi do\n454\t4:\n455\tfor each term t ∈ E XTRACT T ERMS(hi ) do\n456\t5:\n457\tC[t] += 1\n458\t6:\n459\tend for\n460\t7: end for\n461\t8: G ← top-k surface forms of C by frequency\n462\t9: Pass 2: h′i ← M (si | G) for all si ▷ glossary as context\n463\tEnsure: refined transcripts {h′1 , . . . , h′n }\n464\t\n465\tcap it at 160 tokens, and we decode greedily. For Qwen3-ASR,\n466\twe pass the glossary through the native context field as a system\n467\tmessage. The instruction tells the model to use the context for\n468\ttechnical-term disambiguation and not to copy unspoken text.\n469\tWe call this last constraint the guard sentence. Qwen3-ASR is\n470\ttrained to treat such context as background knowledge [11], so\n471\tthe design matches the model.\n472\tContext variants. We compare the first-pass glossary\n473\tagainst five alternative context sources and an oracle upper\n474\tbound.\n475\t• Title: the lecture title only.\n476\t• Prev-ASR: the previous five first-pass segments.\n477\t• Combined: joins the lecture title, prev-ASR segments,\n478\tand first-pass glossary.\n479\t• External list: a fixed, course-level ML/LLM term list,\n480\tranked by lecture-title match.\n481\t• Hybrid: fills the first 15 prompt slots from the external\n482\tlist and the remaining slots from the first-pass glossary.\n483\t• Oracle: prompts with terms from the reference transcript. Not deployable; reported as an upper bound only.\n484\t\n485\tAll variants except the oracle are reference-free.\n486\t\n487\t6. Experiments\n488\tSetup. We decode five backbones with context, and we run\n489\tthe glossary ablations on Breeze-ASR-25. We rescore each\n490\tsegment-only baseline on the 5.01-hour term-rich subset, so its\n491\tCER is comparable to the contextual rows. These subset CERs\n492\tare higher than the full-set CERs in Table 2, because the termrich subset is harder. We decode greedily unless stated otherwise. We test significance with a paired bootstrap over segments, using 2,000 resamples. All term-recall gains below are\n493\tsignificant at p < 0.001 [17].\n494\tMain result. Table 3 reports the contextual results. The\n495\tfirst-pass glossary raises term recall for all five backbones. The\n496\tgain ranges from +6.95 on whisper-large-v3-turbo to +9.45 on\n497\tQwen3-ASR-0.6B across the four competitive backbones, and\n498\tit reaches +17.59 on the weak Breeze-ASR-26. The glossary\n499\talso holds or lowers CER on all five models. On Breeze-ASR25 it cuts CER from 11.37% to 9.79% while lifting recall from\n500\t52.50% to 60.13%.\n501\tCombined context vs. first-pass glossary. The combined\n502\tcontext (title + prev-ASR + glossary) helps some models and\n503\thurts others. It gives the best recall on Qwen3-ASR-1.7B and\n504\ton the weak Breeze-ASR-26, but it raises CER on whisperlarge-v3-turbo to 15.89% and on Qwen3-ASR-0.6B to 25.39%.\n505\tThe added length is the cause. A small model cannot manage\n506\tlong context, so the extra text corrupts decoding. The raw prevASR context is the worst case: on Qwen3-ASR-0.6B it alone\n507\tdrives CER to 34.01%, because the model copies whole misrecognized sentences. The first-pass glossary avoids this failure.\n508\tIt is short, and it improves recall on every model. The glossary\n509\tis therefore the robust first choice, and the combined context is\n510\ta per-model option.\n511\tClosing the headroom. The oracle sits well above every deployable setting, at 68.88% recall on Breeze-ASR-25,\n512\t64.41% on Qwen3-ASR-1.7B, and 62.84% on Qwen3-ASR-\n513\t\n514\t\fTable 4: Term-source comparison on Breeze-ASR-25 over the\n515\t5.01 h term-rich set. First-pass glossary: terms extracted from\n516\tthe model’s own first-pass output. External list: a fixed courselevel ML/LLM term list. Hybrid: first 15 slots from the external\n517\tlist, rest from the first-pass glossary. Oracle: terms from the\n518\treference transcript (upper bound, not deployable). ⋆ marks\n519\treference-free settings. Bold marks the best deployable value\n520\tper column. All values are percentages; lower is better for CER\n521\tand TermER.\n522\tSource\n523\t\n524\tCER\n525\t\n526\tRecall\n527\t\n528\tPrec.\n529\t\n530\tF1\n531\t\n532\tTermER\n533\t\n534\tbaseline (segment-only)\n535\tfirst-pass glossary ⋆\n536\texternal list ⋆\n537\thybrid ⋆\n538\t\n539\t11.37\n540\t9.79\n541\t10.04\n542\t9.40\n543\t\n544\t52.50\n545\t60.13\n546\t60.29\n547\t62.05\n548\t\n549\t80.55\n550\t81.20\n551\t81.89\n552\t82.73\n553\t\n554\t63.57\n555\t69.09\n556\t69.45\n557\t70.91\n558\t\n559\t48.66\n560\t41.38\n561\t41.38\n562\t39.39\n563\t\n564\toracle (reference)\n565\t\n566\t8.19\n567\t\n568\t68.88\n569\t\n570\t86.70\n571\t\n572\t76.77\n573\t\n574\t32.71\n575\t\n576\t0.6B. The gap is mostly a coverage problem. Of the terms\n577\tonly the oracle recovers, 55% to 65% never appear in any firstpass hypothesis. These are lecture-specific names: OpenClaw\n578\tis heard as “open cloud”, ACON as “Aiken”, and AppWorld as\n579\t“app world”. A first-pass glossary cannot recover them, so we\n580\tadd a small external list of 15 course-level terms per lecture,\n581\twhich still uses no reference transcript. Table 4 compares the\n582\tsources on Breeze-ASR-25. The external list alone matches the\n583\tfirst-pass glossary. The hybrid of the two reaches 62.05% recall and 9.40% CER, a significant +1.92 recall gain over the\n584\tfirst-pass glossary. Relative to the segment-only baseline, the\n585\thybrid improves all four term metrics at once: it raises recall\n586\tfrom 52.50% to 62.05% and precision from 80.55% to 82.73%,\n587\tlifts F1 from 63.57% to 70.91%, and lowers CER from 11.37%\n588\tto 9.40%, each significant at p < 0.001. The gain is therefore\n589\tnot a recall-for-precision trade. It is the strongest deployable\n590\tsetting we test.\n591\t6.1. Analysis\n592\tGlossary size. We sweep the glossary size on Breeze-ASR-25\n593\tover k ∈ {10, 20, 30, 50, 100, all}. Recall rises with k and saturates near k=100, since each lecture yields at most 106 firstpass candidates. CER is lowest at k=30 (9.79%), and term F1\n594\tpeaks at k=50 (69.50%). Beyond k=50, the recall gain shrinks\n595\twhile CER rises and precision drops. We keep k=30 as a compact operating point that gives the lowest CER and near-peak\n596\tF1.\n597\tTerm-selection criterion. We fix k=30 and change how\n598\tthe 30 terms are chosen. Frequency ranking gives the best recall (60.13%), F1, and CER. First-occurrence (57.27%) and random (58.58%) selection are significantly worse. Downweighting generic terms stays close on recall (59.90%) but still lowers\n599\tF1 and precision. The bursty repeat count, not the mere presence of a term, is what makes the glossary work.\n600\tWhere it helps. The recall gain spans all four term kinds\n601\t(Table 5). It is concentrated on acronyms and model names for\n602\tBreeze-ASR-25, and on acronyms and multi-word terms for the\n603\tsmall Qwen3-ASR-0.6B, so a weak baseline has the most term\n604\theadroom to recover. Every per-category gain is significant under paired bootstrap. For Qwen3, the guard sentence protects\n605\tprecision: removing it lowers precision on Qwen3-ASR-0.6B\n606\tby 1.39 points and raises its CER.\n607\tRobustness checks. Under beam search (b=5) the recall\n608\tgain holds at +7.56 and CER is non-worse, so it is not a greedydecoding effect. The first-pass glossaries are clean: weighted\n609\t\n610\tTable 5: Per-category term-recall gain (percentage points) of\n611\tthe first-pass glossary over segment-only decoding, on the 5.01\n612\th term-rich set, split by the four reference term kinds. All gains\n613\tare significant under paired bootstrap (p < 0.01).\n614\tModel\n615\t\n616\tAcronym\n617\t\n618\tModel/Name\n619\t\n620\tCode\n621\t\n622\tMulti-word\n623\t\n624\tBreeze-ASR-25\n625\tQwen3-ASR-1.7B\n626\tQwen3-ASR-0.6B\n627\t\n628\t+13.37\n629\t+10.54\n630\t+15.68\n631\t\n632\t+9.31\n633\t+5.70\n634\t+5.50\n635\t\n636\t+6.03\n637\t+6.60\n638\t+1.97\n639\t\n640\t+4.08\n641\t+10.04\n642\t+14.89\n643\t\n644\tpurity is 95.56% on Breeze-ASR-25, 92.19% on Qwen3-ASR1.7B, and 90.75% on Qwen3-ASR-0.6B, so the reference-free\n645\tlist is mostly real lecture terms. A third decoding pass that rebuilds the glossary from the second-pass output raises recall by\n646\ta further +0.90 to 61.03%, but it does not improve F1, CER, or\n647\tterm error rate, because precision falls as the glossary grows.\n648\tOne refinement pass is therefore enough. The glossary also\n649\trescues near-miss forms: “aia” becomes AI agent, “lnn” becomes llm, “pump” becomes prompt, and “SW1 bench” becomes SWE-bench.\n650\t\n651\t7. Conclusion\n652\tWe studied ASR for Mandarin technical lectures, where CER\n653\thides technical-term failures. We measured term recognition\n654\tdirectly with term recall, precision, F1, and term error rate, and\n655\twe proposed a two-pass, reference-free glossary prompt built\n656\tfrom first-pass hypotheses. It raises term recall on all five backbones while holding or lowering CER, and the lecture-level frequency of the terms, not their mere presence, drives the gain.\n657\tOn Breeze-ASR-25 a hybrid with a small external list reaches\n658\t62.05% term recall and 9.40% CER.\n659\tThe method reframes contextual biasing as retrieval over\n660\tthe recording itself: the first pass retrieves, and the second\n661\tpass conditions on the retrieved terms with no external catalog. Because term burstiness drives the gain, it should carry\n662\tto other long-form code-switched audio such as meetings and\n663\tseminars. The benchmark and the term-centric metrics also\n664\ttransfer: any domain with specialized vocabulary and low-CER\n665\tmodels would benefit from evaluation that separates term accuracy from overall character accuracy.\n666\tSeveral limitations remain. The benchmark covers one instructor and one domain (AI/ML). Multi-speaker and crossdomain evaluation, for example on medical or legal lectures,\n667\twould test whether the burstiness assumption generalizes. The\n668\tterm extractor is rule-based, so it misses terms that do not match\n669\tpre-defined patterns. A learned extractor could improve both\n670\tbenchmark coverage and first-pass glossary quality. The largest\n671\topen gap is coverage: 55% to 65% of oracle-only terms never\n672\tappear in any first-pass hypothesis, because the model has never\n673\tseen the surface form. Closing this gap may require retrieval\n674\tfrom course-level materials such as slides and syllabi, which\n675\tare typically available in educational settings.\n676\t\n677\t8. References\n678\t[1] D.-C. Lyu, T.-P. Tan, E. S. Chng, and H. Li, “SEAME: A\n679\tMandarin-English code-switching speech corpus in South-East\n680\tAsia,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2010, pp. 1986–1989.\n681\t[2] X. Shi, Q. Feng, and L. Xie, “The ASRU 2019 Mandarin-English\n682\tcode-switching speech recognition challenge: Open datasets,\n683\ttracks, methods and results,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2007.05916,\n684\t2020.\n685\t[3] H. Lovenia, S. Cahyawijaya, G. I. Winata, P. Xu, Y. Xu, Z. Liu,\n686\t\n687\t\fR. Frieske, T. Yu, W. Dai, E. J. Barezi, Q. Chen, X. Ma, B. E. Shi,\n688\tand P. Fung, “ASCEND: A spontaneous Chinese-English dataset\n689\tfor code-switching in multi-turn conversation,” in Proc. Language\n690\tResources and Evaluation Conference (LREC), 2022, pp. 7259–\n691\t7268.\n692\t[4] C.-K. Chou, C.-J. Hsu, H.-L. Chung, L.-H. Tseng, H.-C. Cheng,\n693\tY.-K. Fu, K.-P. Huang, and H.-Y. Lee, “A self-refining framework\n694\tfor enhancing ASR using TTS-synthesized data,” arXiv preprint\n695\tarXiv:2506.11130, 2025.\n696\t[5] L.-H. Tseng, Z.-C. Chen, K.-W. Chang, C.-H. Lee, K.-P. Huang,\n697\tand H.-Y. Lee, “Leveraging language-specific knowledge for\n698\tcode-switching ASR via knowledge distillation,” in Proc. IEEE\n699\tSpoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT), 2024.\n700\t[6] G. Pundak, T. N. Sainath, R. Prabhavalkar, A. Kannan, and\n701\tD. Zhao, “Deep context: End-to-end contextual speech recognition,” in Proc. IEEE Spoken Language Technology Workshop\n702\t(SLT), 2018.\n703\t[7] D. Le, M. Jain, G. Keren, S. Kim, Y. Shi, J. Mahadeokar, J. Chan,\n704\tY. Shangguan, C. Fuegen, O. Kalinli, Y. Saraf, and M. L. Seltzer,\n705\t“Contextualized streaming end-to-end speech recognition with\n706\ttrie-based deep biasing and shallow fusion,” in Proc. Interspeech,\n707\t2021.\n708\t[8] Y. Chu, J. Xu, X. Zhou, Q. Yang, S. Zhang, Z. Yan, C. Zhou, and\n709\tJ. Zhou, “Qwen-Audio: Advancing universal audio understanding via unified large-scale audio-language models,” arXiv preprint\n710\tarXiv:2311.07919, 2023.\n711\t[9] C. Tang, W. Yu, G. Sun, X. Chen, T. Tan, W. Li, L. Lu, Z. Ma,\n712\tand C. Zhang, “SALMONN: Towards generic hearing abilities\n713\tfor large language models,” in Proc. International Conference on\n714\tLearning Representations (ICLR), 2024.\n715\t[10] Y. Bai, J. Chen, J. Chen, W. Chen, Z. Chen, C. Ding et al., “SeedASR: Understanding diverse speech and contexts with LLMbased speech recognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2407.04675,\n716\t2024.\n717\t[11] Qwen Team, “Qwen3-ASR technical report,” arXiv preprint\n718\tarXiv:2601.21337, 2026.\n719\t[12] A. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and\n720\tI. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision,” in Proc. International Conference on Machine Learning (ICML), 2023.\n721\t[13] T. N. Sainath, R. Pang, D. Rybach, Y. He, R. Prabhavalkar, W. Li,\n722\tM. Visontai, Q. Liang, T. Strohman, Y. Wu, I. McGraw, and C.-C.\n723\tChiu, “Two-pass end-to-end speech recognition,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2019, pp. 2773–2777.\n724\t[14] K. Hu, T. N. Sainath, R. Pang, and R. Prabhavalkar, “Deliberation\n725\tmodel based two-pass end-to-end speech recognition,” in Proc.\n726\tIEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\n727\tProcessing (ICASSP), 2020, pp. 7799–7803.\n728\t[15] C. Chen, Y. Hu, C.-H. H. Yang, S. M. Siniscalchi, P.-Y. Chen, and\n729\tE. S. Chng, “HyPoradise: An open baseline for generative speech\n730\trecognition with large language models,” in Advances in Neural\n731\tInformation Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2023.\n732\t[16] P. Lewis, E. Perez, A. Piktus, F. Petroni, V. Karpukhin, N. Goyal,\n733\tH. Küttler, M. Lewis, W.-t. Yih, T. Rocktäschel, S. Riedel,\n734\tand D. Kiela, “Retrieval-augmented generation for knowledgeintensive NLP tasks,” in Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2020.\n735\t[17] P. Koehn, “Statistical significance tests for machine translation\n736\tevaluation,” in Proc. Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Processing (EMNLP), 2004.\n737\t\n738\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b18d56d6-b0d3-4f0e-aaa3-e348a3b255ac", "uuid": "4f2b4e1f-81b9-4d7c-8132-02682eadd1da", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T11:32:06.112Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.05058.txt", "content": "Context-Aware ASR for Mandarin Technical Lectures\nHo-Lam Chung1,2 , Yiming Chen2 , Hung-yi Lee1\n1\n\nNational Taiwan University, Taiwan\n\n2\n\nASUS\n\nholam.chung@protonmail.com, yiming.chen@u.nus.edu, tlkagkb93901106@gmail.com\n\narXiv:2607.05058v1 [cs.SD] 6 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract\nTechnical lectures mix Mandarin speech with English technical terms. These terms carry the core meaning of the lecture,\nyet they occupy few characters. Character error rate (CER)\ntherefore hides their recognition failures. We study whether\nlecture context helps recognize these terms. We build a termrich Mandarin AI/ML lecture benchmark, and we define termcentric metrics that measure technical-term recognition directly.\nWe then propose a two-pass, reference-free decoding method.\nThe first pass runs segment-only ASR. We extract the most frequent technical terms from the first-pass hypotheses, and we\nprompt the recognizer with this self-built glossary in the second pass. Across five ASR backbones, the first-pass glossary\nraises term recall for every model and holds or lowers CER on\nall five. On Breeze-ASR-25 it lifts term recall from 52.50% to\n60.13% while lowering CER, and a hybrid that adds a small\nexternal term list reaches 62.05% recall and 82.73% term precision. Lecture context, recovered from the model’s own output,\nis a practical signal for technical-term recognition. Term-centric\nevaluation exposes errors that CER misses.\nIndex Terms: speech recognition, code-switching, contextual\nbiasing, technical terms, Mandarin\n\n1. Introduction\nLecture ASR powers subtitles, search, and note-taking for students. In AI/ML lectures, bilingual technical terms anchor the\ncontent. Terms such as RAG, SWE-bench, AI Agent, token, and\nembedding name the concepts the speaker explains. A student\nwho reads “RIG” instead of “RAG” loses the point of the segment.\nThese terms occupy a small fraction of the characters. A\ntranscript can reach low CER while still misrecognizing the key\nterm. The Mandarin around the term is fluent, so CER stays low.\nThe usable content, however, is wrong. CER does not capture\nthis failure.\nLecture terms are bursty. Once the speaker introduces AI\nAgent, the term recurs across many later segments. The lecture\ntitle, the previous transcript, and the repeated terms all point\nto the same vocabulary. Segment-only decoding discards this\nsignal. It recognizes each segment in isolation, so it cannot use\nthe strong context that the lecture provides.\nWe address this gap by building a term-rich benchmark,\nmeasuring term recognition directly, and supplying a self-built\nglossary as decoding context.\nOur contributions are as follows.\n• We release a term-rich Mandarin AI/ML lecture ASR\nbenchmark. It contains 8,888 technical-term occurrences\nover a 5.01-hour code-switched test set.\n• We define term-centric evaluation. It reports term recall,\nterm precision, term F1, and term error rate, so it separates technical-term accuracy from overall CER.\n\n• We propose a two-pass, reference-free glossary prompt.\nIt extracts a lecture glossary from first-pass hypotheses,\nand it improves term recall across five ASR backbones\nwhile holding or lowering CER on all of them. A hybrid\nthat adds a small external glossary reaches 62.05% term\nrecall on Breeze-ASR-25, closing part of the remaining\nheadroom.\n\n2. Related Work\nCode-switching Mandarin-English ASR. Mandarin-English\ncode-switching is a long-standing challenge for ASR. Public\ncorpora such as SEAME [1], the ASRU 2019 challenge set [2],\nand ASCEND [3] established Mandarin-English benchmarks,\nbut they target conversational rather than lecture speech. Recent work fine-tunes large models on Mandarin with English\nterms [4], and distills language-specific knowledge for codeswitching [5]. These methods improve the acoustic model. We\ninstead keep the model frozen, and we add context at decoding\ntime.\nContextual biasing. Contextual ASR injects external\nknowledge into recognition. Deep context learns to bias toward a phrase list [6]. Trie-based deep biasing and shallow fusion bias streaming recognizers toward a catalog [7]. Audiolanguage models couple speech encoders with LLMs [8, 9],\nand LLM-based recognizers consume free-form context [10].\nQwen3-ASR treats context tokens as background knowledge\nfor biasing [11]. These methods assume a context source is\navailable. We build the context from the model’s own first-pass\noutput, so the method needs no external list.\nPrompting and retrieval. Whisper accepts an initial\nprompt that conditions decoding [12]. Two-pass ASR refines\nfirst-pass output, either by rescoring streamed hypotheses with\na second decoder [13, 14] or by correcting the first-pass N-best\nlist with an LLM [15]. Retrieval-augmented generation supplies retrieved evidence to a generator [16]. Our two-pass glossary is an in-domain analogue: the first pass retrieves over the\nlecture itself, and the second pass conditions on the retrieved\nterms. Unlike rescoring or correction, we feed the terms back\nas context rather than editing the hypotheses, and we derive that\nlist from the model’s own lecture-level output, so the method is\nreference-free.\n\n3. Benchmark\nWe build the benchmark from a publicly available MandarinEnglish AI/ML lecture series1 . The lectures are spontaneous\nspeech, with English technical terms code-switched into Mandarin. We segment the lectures and pair each segment with its\nreference transcript.\nWe then build a term-rich test set. A rule-based recognizer\nextracts technical terms from the reference transcripts. It tar1 Dataset, code, and term metadata will be released upon publication.\n\n\fTable 1: Benchmark statistics. The term-rich test set isolates\nsegments that contain at least one technical term.\nItem\n\nValue\n\nFull set segments\nFull set duration\nTerm-rich segments\nTerm-rich duration\nTerm occurrences\nUnique canonical terms\nLectures\n\n29,043\n16.92 h\n7,443\n5.01 h\n8,888\n1,030\n15\n\ntoken\nAI\nattention\nprompt\nAI Agent\nembedding\ncontext\nagent\nOpenClaw\nsequence\nLlama\nlayer\n\n230\n204\n176\n135\n132\n116\n108\n\n0\n\n372\n338\n312\n292\n\n784\n\n200\n400\n600\n800\nOccurrences in term-rich test set\n\nFigure 1: Technical-term frequency in the term-rich test set, top\n12 terms. The distribution is heavy-tailed. The lecture-specific\ntool name OpenClaw (red) occurs 135 times, which shows that\neven a name the model has never seen repeats heavily within\none lecture.\n\ngets four kinds of terms: acronyms such as AI and LLM; model\nand tool names such as Llama, Whisper, and OpenClaw; codelike strings such as SWE-bench and log1.txt; and multi-word\nterms such as AI Agent and Context Engineering. We canonicalize each term with NFKC normalization, lowercasing, and\nlight stemming, so surface variants map to one key. A segment\nenters the term-rich set when it contains at least one term.\nTable 1 summarizes the benchmark. The full set has 29,043\nsegments and 16.92 hours. The term-rich test set has 7,443 segments and 5.01 hours, with 8,888 term occurrences and 1,030\nunique terms over 15 lectures. Terms are bursty. Fig. 1 shows\nthe term frequencies. The term token occurs 784 times, AI\nAgent 292 times, and the lecture-specific name OpenClaw 135\ntimes. This burstiness is the signal that motivates lecture-level\ncontext. The distribution is heavy-tailed: acronyms and short\nmodel names lead the head, while multi-word terms and codelike strings fill the tail. A method must handle both the frequent\nacronyms and the rare composite names.\n\n4. Term-Centric Evaluation\nCER measures character accuracy over the whole segment. It\ndoes not tell us whether the recognizer captured the technical\nterms. We therefore add four term-centric metrics. We compute\nthem over canonical term keys.\nWe define term recall as the fraction of reference term oc-\n\nTable 2: Segment-only baselines. CER is computed on the full\n16.92 h set; term metrics on the 5.01 h term-rich subset. All\nvalues are percentages. Bold marks the best column value,\nunderline the second best. Lower is better for CER and TermER; higher is better otherwise.\nModel\n\nCER\n\nRecall\n\nPrec.\n\nF1\n\nTermER\n\nBreeze-ASR-25\nwhisper-l-v3-turbo\nQwen3-ASR-1.7B\nQwen3-ASR-0.6B\nBreeze-ASR-26\n\n10.72\n11.95\n15.28\n16.64\n24.63\n\n52.50\n53.90\n49.03\n44.28\n27.31\n\n80.55\n65.11\n72.84\n71.19\n56.26\n\n63.57\n58.98\n58.61\n54.60\n36.77\n\n48.66\n49.67\n53.31\n58.20\n75.14\n\ncurrences whose canonical key appears in the hypothesis of the\nsame segment. We define term precision as the fraction of predicted term keys that appear in the reference. We define term F1\nas their harmonic mean. We define term error rate as the edit\ndistance between the reference and hypothesis term sequences,\nnormalized by the reference term count.\nWe keep CER as the overall accuracy measure. We normalize all Mandarin text with OpenCC2 (s2twp) and apply NFKC\nand lowercasing before scoring. A usable transcript needs both\nhigh recall and high precision, and CER captures neither. The\ntwo metrics can move in opposite directions: a recognizer that\ncopies a long context into its output raises recall while collapsing precision, as Table 3 shows. We therefore report recall and\nprecision together, and treat term recall as the headline metric\nbecause it counts how many technical terms the recognizer recovered.\nTable 2 reports five recognizers under segment-only decoding. Breeze-ASR-25 has the best CER and the best term error\nrate. Yet it recovers only 52.50% of the terms. Whisper-largev3-turbo has slightly higher term recall but much lower term\nprecision. Every model leaves a large share of technical terms\nunrecognized. A low CER does not imply usable technical transcripts.\n\n5. Method\nWe propose a two-pass, reference-free decoding method. We\ncall it ASR - GLOSSARY. The idea is simple. A lecture repeats\nits terms, so the model’s own first-pass output already contains\nthose terms. We collect them, and we feed them back as context.\nAlgorithm 1 states the procedure. The first pass runs\nsegment-only ASR over the lecture. We extract canonical terms\nfrom every first-pass hypothesis, and we rank them by frequency across the lecture. We keep the top k surface forms\nas the first-pass glossary. The second pass re-decodes each segment with this glossary as context.\nWe set k = 30. A short glossary keeps the prompt compact,\nso it avoids over-conditioning. Frequency ranking captures the\nbursty repeats, so the glossary holds the terms that matter for\nthis lecture. A sweep over k (Sec. 6.1) confirms that k = 30\ngives the lowest CER, and a selection ablation confirms that\nlecture-level frequency, not the mere presence of a term, is the\nsignal that matters. We use the surface form, so the prompt\nreads like natural text.\nConditioning interface. The two model families consume\nthe glossary differently. For Whisper-family models, including Breeze, we pass the glossary as an initial prompt through\nprompt tokens. We apply it to the first decoding window, we\n2 https://github.com/BYVoid/OpenCC\n\n\fTable 3: Contextual decoding across five ASR backbones on the 5.01 h term-rich set. CER is rescored on this subset, so baselines match\nthe contextual rows. ∆R is the term-recall gain over the baseline. ⋆ marks the proposed reference-free prompt. Bold marks the best\nvalue per column within each model. Values are percentages; lower is better for CER and TermER.\n\nModel\n\nContext\n\nCER\n\nRecall\n\n∆R\n\nPrec.\n\nF1\n\nTermER\n\nBreeze-ASR-25\n\nbaseline (segment-only)\n+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n\n11.37\n9.79\n9.19\n\n52.50\n60.13\n59.51\n\n–\n+7.63\n+7.01\n\n80.55\n81.20\n82.19\n\n63.57\n69.09\n69.03\n\n48.66\n41.38\n41.74\n\nwhisper-l-v3-turbo\n\nbaseline (segment-only)\n+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n\n13.80\n12.82\n15.89\n\n53.90\n60.86\n59.74\n\n–\n+6.95\n+5.84\n\n65.11\n63.79\n65.03\n\n58.98\n62.29\n62.28\n\n49.67\n45.93\n48.77\n\nQwen3-ASR-1.7B\n\nbaseline (segment-only)\n+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n\n16.13\n14.02\n13.93\n\n49.03\n56.56\n56.60\n\n–\n+7.53\n+7.57\n\n72.84\n74.43\n76.11\n\n58.61\n64.27\n64.92\n\n53.31\n47.10\n46.26\n\nQwen3-ASR-0.6B\n\nbaseline (segment-only)\n+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n\n18.91\n18.86\n25.39\n\n44.28\n53.74\n54.43\n\n–\n+9.45\n+10.15\n\n71.19\n65.92\n59.79\n\n54.60\n59.21\n56.99\n\n58.20\n54.64\n64.99\n\nBreeze-ASR-26\n\nbaseline (segment-only)\n+ first-pass glossary (k=30) ⋆\n+ title + prev-ASR + glossary\n\n38.28\n26.05\n21.67\n\n27.31\n44.89\n49.73\n\n–\n+17.59\n+22.42\n\n56.26\n57.15\n63.32\n\n36.77\n50.28\n55.71\n\n75.14\n62.27\n54.53\n\nAlgorithm 1 Two-pass glossary-prompted decoding\nRequire: lecture segments S = {s1 , . . . , sn }, recognizer M ,\nglossary size k\n1: Pass 1: hi ← M (si ) for all si\n▷ segment-only\n2: C ← C OUNTER()\n3: for each hi do\n4:\nfor each term t ∈ E XTRACT T ERMS(hi ) do\n5:\nC[t] += 1\n6:\nend for\n7: end for\n8: G ← top-k surface forms of C by frequency\n9: Pass 2: h′i ← M (si | G) for all si ▷ glossary as context\nEnsure: refined transcripts {h′1 , . . . , h′n }\n\ncap it at 160 tokens, and we decode greedily. For Qwen3-ASR,\nwe pass the glossary through the native context field as a system\nmessage. The instruction tells the model to use the context for\ntechnical-term disambiguation and not to copy unspoken text.\nWe call this last constraint the guard sentence. Qwen3-ASR is\ntrained to treat such context as background knowledge [11], so\nthe design matches the model.\nContext variants. We compare the first-pass glossary\nagainst five alternative context sources and an oracle upper\nbound.\n• Title: the lecture title only.\n• Prev-ASR: the previous five first-pass segments.\n• Combined: joins the lecture title, prev-ASR segments,\nand first-pass glossary.\n• External list: a fixed, course-level ML/LLM term list,\nranked by lecture-title match.\n• Hybrid: fills the first 15 prompt slots from the external\nlist and the remaining slots from the first-pass glossary.\n• Oracle: prompts with terms from the reference transcript. Not deployable; reported as an upper bound only.\n\nAll variants except the oracle are reference-free.\n\n6. Experiments\nSetup. We decode five backbones with context, and we run\nthe glossary ablations on Breeze-ASR-25. We rescore each\nsegment-only baseline on the 5.01-hour term-rich subset, so its\nCER is comparable to the contextual rows. These subset CERs\nare higher than the full-set CERs in Table 2, because the termrich subset is harder. We decode greedily unless stated otherwise. We test significance with a paired bootstrap over segments, using 2,000 resamples. All term-recall gains below are\nsignificant at p < 0.001 [17].\nMain result. Table 3 reports the contextual results. The\nfirst-pass glossary raises term recall for all five backbones. The\ngain ranges from +6.95 on whisper-large-v3-turbo to +9.45 on\nQwen3-ASR-0.6B across the four competitive backbones, and\nit reaches +17.59 on the weak Breeze-ASR-26. The glossary\nalso holds or lowers CER on all five models. On Breeze-ASR25 it cuts CER from 11.37% to 9.79% while lifting recall from\n52.50% to 60.13%.\nCombined context vs. first-pass glossary. The combined\ncontext (title + prev-ASR + glossary) helps some models and\nhurts others. It gives the best recall on Qwen3-ASR-1.7B and\non the weak Breeze-ASR-26, but it raises CER on whisperlarge-v3-turbo to 15.89% and on Qwen3-ASR-0.6B to 25.39%.\nThe added length is the cause. A small model cannot manage\nlong context, so the extra text corrupts decoding. The raw prevASR context is the worst case: on Qwen3-ASR-0.6B it alone\ndrives CER to 34.01%, because the model copies whole misrecognized sentences. The first-pass glossary avoids this failure.\nIt is short, and it improves recall on every model. The glossary\nis therefore the robust first choice, and the combined context is\na per-model option.\nClosing the headroom. The oracle sits well above every deployable setting, at 68.88% recall on Breeze-ASR-25,\n64.41% on Qwen3-ASR-1.7B, and 62.84% on Qwen3-ASR-\n\n\fTable 4: Term-source comparison on Breeze-ASR-25 over the\n5.01 h term-rich set. First-pass glossary: terms extracted from\nthe model’s own first-pass output. External list: a fixed courselevel ML/LLM term list. Hybrid: first 15 slots from the external\nlist, rest from the first-pass glossary. Oracle: terms from the\nreference transcript (upper bound, not deployable). ⋆ marks\nreference-free settings. Bold marks the best deployable value\nper column. All values are percentages; lower is better for CER\nand TermER.\nSource\n\nCER\n\nRecall\n\nPrec.\n\nF1\n\nTermER\n\nbaseline (segment-only)\nfirst-pass glossary ⋆\nexternal list ⋆\nhybrid ⋆\n\n11.37\n9.79\n10.04\n9.40\n\n52.50\n60.13\n60.29\n62.05\n\n80.55\n81.20\n81.89\n82.73\n\n63.57\n69.09\n69.45\n70.91\n\n48.66\n41.38\n41.38\n39.39\n\noracle (reference)\n\n8.19\n\n68.88\n\n86.70\n\n76.77\n\n32.71\n\n0.6B. The gap is mostly a coverage problem. Of the terms\nonly the oracle recovers, 55% to 65% never appear in any firstpass hypothesis. These are lecture-specific names: OpenClaw\nis heard as “open cloud”, ACON as “Aiken”, and AppWorld as\n“app world”. A first-pass glossary cannot recover them, so we\nadd a small external list of 15 course-level terms per lecture,\nwhich still uses no reference transcript. Table 4 compares the\nsources on Breeze-ASR-25. The external list alone matches the\nfirst-pass glossary. The hybrid of the two reaches 62.05% recall and 9.40% CER, a significant +1.92 recall gain over the\nfirst-pass glossary. Relative to the segment-only baseline, the\nhybrid improves all four term metrics at once: it raises recall\nfrom 52.50% to 62.05% and precision from 80.55% to 82.73%,\nlifts F1 from 63.57% to 70.91%, and lowers CER from 11.37%\nto 9.40%, each significant at p < 0.001. The gain is therefore\nnot a recall-for-precision trade. It is the strongest deployable\nsetting we test.\n6.1. Analysis\nGlossary size. We sweep the glossary size on Breeze-ASR-25\nover k ∈ {10, 20, 30, 50, 100, all}. Recall rises with k and saturates near k=100, since each lecture yields at most 106 firstpass candidates. CER is lowest at k=30 (9.79%), and term F1\npeaks at k=50 (69.50%). Beyond k=50, the recall gain shrinks\nwhile CER rises and precision drops. We keep k=30 as a compact operating point that gives the lowest CER and near-peak\nF1.\nTerm-selection criterion. We fix k=30 and change how\nthe 30 terms are chosen. Frequency ranking gives the best recall (60.13%), F1, and CER. First-occurrence (57.27%) and random (58.58%) selection are significantly worse. Downweighting generic terms stays close on recall (59.90%) but still lowers\nF1 and precision. The bursty repeat count, not the mere presence of a term, is what makes the glossary work.\nWhere it helps. The recall gain spans all four term kinds\n(Table 5). It is concentrated on acronyms and model names for\nBreeze-ASR-25, and on acronyms and multi-word terms for the\nsmall Qwen3-ASR-0.6B, so a weak baseline has the most term\nheadroom to recover. Every per-category gain is significant under paired bootstrap. For Qwen3, the guard sentence protects\nprecision: removing it lowers precision on Qwen3-ASR-0.6B\nby 1.39 points and raises its CER.\nRobustness checks. Under beam search (b=5) the recall\ngain holds at +7.56 and CER is non-worse, so it is not a greedydecoding effect. The first-pass glossaries are clean: weighted\n\nTable 5: Per-category term-recall gain (percentage points) of\nthe first-pass glossary over segment-only decoding, on the 5.01\nh term-rich set, split by the four reference term kinds. All gains\nare significant under paired bootstrap (p < 0.01).\nModel\n\nAcronym\n\nModel/Name\n\nCode\n\nMulti-word\n\nBreeze-ASR-25\nQwen3-ASR-1.7B\nQwen3-ASR-0.6B\n\n+13.37\n+10.54\n+15.68\n\n+9.31\n+5.70\n+5.50\n\n+6.03\n+6.60\n+1.97\n\n+4.08\n+10.04\n+14.89\n\npurity is 95.56% on Breeze-ASR-25, 92.19% on Qwen3-ASR1.7B, and 90.75% on Qwen3-ASR-0.6B, so the reference-free\nlist is mostly real lecture terms. A third decoding pass that rebuilds the glossary from the second-pass output raises recall by\na further +0.90 to 61.03%, but it does not improve F1, CER, or\nterm error rate, because precision falls as the glossary grows.\nOne refinement pass is therefore enough. The glossary also\nrescues near-miss forms: “aia” becomes AI agent, “lnn” becomes llm, “pump” becomes prompt, and “SW1 bench” becomes SWE-bench.\n\n7. Conclusion\nWe studied ASR for Mandarin technical lectures, where CER\nhides technical-term failures. We measured term recognition\ndirectly with term recall, precision, F1, and term error rate, and\nwe proposed a two-pass, reference-free glossary prompt built\nfrom first-pass hypotheses. It raises term recall on all five backbones while holding or lowering CER, and the lecture-level frequency of the terms, not their mere presence, drives the gain.\nOn Breeze-ASR-25 a hybrid with a small external list reaches\n62.05% term recall and 9.40% CER.\nThe method reframes contextual biasing as retrieval over\nthe recording itself: the first pass retrieves, and the second\npass conditions on the retrieved terms with no external catalog. Because term burstiness drives the gain, it should carry\nto other long-form code-switched audio such as meetings and\nseminars. The benchmark and the term-centric metrics also\ntransfer: any domain with specialized vocabulary and low-CER\nmodels would benefit from evaluation that separates term accuracy from overall character accuracy.\nSeveral limitations remain. The benchmark covers one instructor and one domain (AI/ML). Multi-speaker and crossdomain evaluation, for example on medical or legal lectures,\nwould test whether the burstiness assumption generalizes. The\nterm extractor is rule-based, so it misses terms that do not match\npre-defined patterns. A learned extractor could improve both\nbenchmark coverage and first-pass glossary quality. The largest\nopen gap is coverage: 55% to 65% of oracle-only terms never\nappear in any first-pass hypothesis, because the model has never\nseen the surface form. Closing this gap may require retrieval\nfrom course-level materials such as slides and syllabi, which\nare typically available in educational settings.\n\n8. References\n[1] D.-C. Lyu, T.-P. Tan, E. S. Chng, and H. Li, “SEAME: A\nMandarin-English code-switching speech corpus in South-East\nAsia,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2010, pp. 1986–1989.\n[2] X. Shi, Q. Feng, and L. Xie, “The ASRU 2019 Mandarin-English\ncode-switching speech recognition challenge: Open datasets,\ntracks, methods and results,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2007.05916,\n2020.\n[3] H. Lovenia, S. Cahyawijaya, G. I. Winata, P. Xu, Y. Xu, Z. Liu,\n\n\fR. Frieske, T. Yu, W. Dai, E. J. Barezi, Q. Chen, X. Ma, B. E. Shi,\nand P. Fung, “ASCEND: A spontaneous Chinese-English dataset\nfor code-switching in multi-turn conversation,” in Proc. Language\nResources and Evaluation Conference (LREC), 2022, pp. 7259–\n7268.\n[4] C.-K. Chou, C.-J. Hsu, H.-L. Chung, L.-H. Tseng, H.-C. Cheng,\nY.-K. Fu, K.-P. Huang, and H.-Y. Lee, “A self-refining framework\nfor enhancing ASR using TTS-synthesized data,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2506.11130, 2025.\n[5] L.-H. Tseng, Z.-C. Chen, K.-W. Chang, C.-H. Lee, K.-P. Huang,\nand H.-Y. Lee, “Leveraging language-specific knowledge for\ncode-switching ASR via knowledge distillation,” in Proc. IEEE\nSpoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT), 2024.\n[6] G. Pundak, T. N. Sainath, R. Prabhavalkar, A. Kannan, and\nD. Zhao, “Deep context: End-to-end contextual speech recognition,” in Proc. IEEE Spoken Language Technology Workshop\n(SLT), 2018.\n[7] D. Le, M. Jain, G. Keren, S. Kim, Y. Shi, J. Mahadeokar, J. Chan,\nY. Shangguan, C. Fuegen, O. Kalinli, Y. Saraf, and M. L. Seltzer,\n“Contextualized streaming end-to-end speech recognition with\ntrie-based deep biasing and shallow fusion,” in Proc. Interspeech,\n2021.\n[8] Y. Chu, J. Xu, X. Zhou, Q. Yang, S. Zhang, Z. Yan, C. Zhou, and\nJ. Zhou, “Qwen-Audio: Advancing universal audio understanding via unified large-scale audio-language models,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2311.07919, 2023.\n[9] C. Tang, W. Yu, G. Sun, X. Chen, T. Tan, W. Li, L. Lu, Z. Ma,\nand C. Zhang, “SALMONN: Towards generic hearing abilities\nfor large language models,” in Proc. International Conference on\nLearning Representations (ICLR), 2024.\n[10] Y. Bai, J. Chen, J. Chen, W. Chen, Z. Chen, C. Ding et al., “SeedASR: Understanding diverse speech and contexts with LLMbased speech recognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2407.04675,\n2024.\n[11] Qwen Team, “Qwen3-ASR technical report,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2601.21337, 2026.\n[12] A. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and\nI. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision,” in Proc. International Conference on Machine Learning (ICML), 2023.\n[13] T. N. Sainath, R. Pang, D. Rybach, Y. He, R. Prabhavalkar, W. Li,\nM. Visontai, Q. Liang, T. Strohman, Y. Wu, I. McGraw, and C.-C.\nChiu, “Two-pass end-to-end speech recognition,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2019, pp. 2773–2777.\n[14] K. Hu, T. N. Sainath, R. Pang, and R. Prabhavalkar, “Deliberation\nmodel based two-pass end-to-end speech recognition,” in Proc.\nIEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\nProcessing (ICASSP), 2020, pp. 7799–7803.\n[15] C. Chen, Y. Hu, C.-H. H. Yang, S. M. Siniscalchi, P.-Y. Chen, and\nE. S. Chng, “HyPoradise: An open baseline for generative speech\nrecognition with large language models,” in Advances in Neural\nInformation Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2023.\n[16] P. Lewis, E. Perez, A. Piktus, F. Petroni, V. Karpukhin, N. Goyal,\nH. Küttler, M. Lewis, W.-t. Yih, T. Rocktäschel, S. Riedel,\nand D. Kiela, “Retrieval-augmented generation for knowledgeintensive NLP tasks,” in Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2020.\n[17] P. Koehn, “Statistical significance tests for machine translation\nevaluation,” in Proc. Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Processing (EMNLP), 2004.\n\n\f", "numLines": 738, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 738}}}
